The magazine controls are ingenious, both in how they have been adapted to the FAL magazine and in how their ergonomics offer the shooter improved control. The magazine catch is a spring-loaded latch that engages the locking lug on the FAL magazine’s upper rear face. The release is fully ambidextrous. When the release is pressed from either side, a lever retracts the latch and the magazine drops free.

Like the magazine catch, the bolt release is a departure. It consists of a one-piece bar that extends across the bottom of the rifle just forward of the trigger guard behind the magazine well. Pressing down on either side releases the bolt. The optional ambidextrous safety transforms the Bushmaster .308 into the only fully ambidextrous AR-type rifle available. The Bushmaster rifle came with an optional Ace Ltd. “ARFX” skeleton stock. This stock replaces the “A2” type fiberglass stock with one of hard anodized aluminum that is both lighter and stronger than the original. The stock has a closed-cell foam cover over the buffer tube. title: Want To Buy:  Yote rifle
postcontent:
I'm wanting to purchase a new rifle for Yote hunting. I am really looking for a Ruger .204 but my second and third choices would be a 22-250 or a .243. 

I know my price range will probably keep me from getting the 22-250 but let's see what we can work out. 

All of that being said, I do have a budget but the budget depends on the rifle and any additional items included. I'm not looking to rip someone off as I'm not looking to be ripped off. I am willing to work out a deal for the right rifle but I will not pay new prices for a used rifle. I know the accessories can add up but I really don't need all of the bells and whistles. I simply need a tack driver at 300 yards that I am not afraid to scratch while in the woods. 

If you have something you think I might be interested in at a fair price, please send me an email with a couple of pictures as well as your asking price. I am not a great negotiator and tend to do my research before making an offer. If I make an offer on your rifle, it will be my best offer. If I feel your asking price is fair after doing some research I will simply accept your price and purchase the gun. If I feel we are too far apart, I will simply let you know I am not interested without making an offer. I do this because I understand that sometimes we carry a personal attachment to a weapon and often value it more than it's actually worth. I know I have several weapons I wouldn't sell unless the deal weighed heavily in my favor.

If you are interested in trading, I may have a few items to trade but I would prefer a cash deal as I don't like to get rid of my stuff :) However, if I need to in order to get the rifle I want, I will work something out.

Sorry for the lengthy message but I didn't want there to be any questions about how I deal. 

I am willing to drive up to an hour or so from Richmond for the right deal and a FTF trade. Even though I am the buyer, I would like to see your Indiana DL as well as complete a simple bill of sale.

Thank you
